                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d163">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">810.20 Defense/52<hi rend="superscript">1/16</hi>:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Honduras</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Erwin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tegucigalpa</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-04T17:00:00-06:00"
                            >June 4, 1940—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 6:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>30. Referring to Department’s telegrams of June 3, 3 p.m.<note n="79"
                        xml:id="d163fn1">See footnote 29, <ref target="#pg_16">p. 16</ref>.</note>
                    and 5 p.m.<note n="80" xml:id="d163fn2">Telegram of June 3, 5 p.m., not found in
                        Department files.</note> 1940, I have conferred with President of
                        Honduras<note n="81" xml:id="d163fn3">Tiburcio Carías Andino.</note> who
                    heartily approves proposal and pledges fullest cooperation of Honduran
                    Government. In order to safeguard secrecy his present plan is to limit his
                    representation to two persons namely his Secretary of War, Navy and Aviation,
                    Juan Galvez and his Minister for Foreign Affairs, Salvador Aguirre.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Erwin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
